node.text: Poor countries are the front lines of climate disaster. So why does news only report on the flooding in Western Europe, but not, say, the devastating drought in Madagascar, the floods in Chad, the wind storm in the Gambia, or the forest fires in the Congo? Are those lives valued less?

node.text: The vast majority of people support a #4DayWorkWeek to reduce unemployment, cut emissions, and improve overall well-being. The only thing standing in our way are some capitalists who, frankly, don't know the meaning of work - truly super-villains. Let us rest!

node.text: The level of moisture in the air affects the elasticity of our vocal cords. Singers can tell you that it's harder to carry a tune in a dry environment. Languages with complex tonality have generally not developed in very cold or dry climates, suggesting that human language is ecologically adaptive.

node.text:
Israel's annexation plan is a geographic mess, and that's by design. Checkerboarding is a colonial tool to create a complex jurisdictional landscape which ultimately constrains sovereignty, and allows settlers to appropriate more and more land. We've seen this before.

Left: The West Bank showing the Green Line and Palestinian Authority land in yellow.
Right: The Uintah and Ouray Indian Reservation in Utah showing tribal trust land in yellow.

node.text:
31 years ago today, Kanien'kehá:ka (Mohawk) warriors and their allies set up a blockade at Ka’neshatà:ke (Oka, QC) to protest the expansion of a golf course onto their territory. Canada's response left 75 warriors wounded and 1 elder dead, and ignited a new generation of Indigenous resistance.⠀
⠀
Áhsen niwáhsen énska niiohserà:ke tsi náhe ⠀
Tsi nén:we eniakwateriiósheke, tsi nén:we eniakwatste'niarónsheke.⠀
⠀
31 years ago today⠀
We will always keep fighting, we will always keep enduring.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Decolonial Atlas on July 10, 2021. May be an image of map and text that says 'TYPES OF TROPICAL AND SUBTROPICAL FORESTS Source: World Wildlife Fund DECOLONIAL ATLAS Tropical and Subtropical Coniferous Forests Tropical and Subtropical Dry Broadleaf Forests Tropical and Subtropical Moist Broadleaf Forests Mediterranean Forests, Woodlands and Scrub Mangroves'.

node.text:
Before the Chicxulub asteroid killed most of the dinosaurs and caused the extinction of about 45% of all tropical plant species, tropical forests were dominated by ferns and large conifers. Compared to today, pre-Chicxulub tropical forests were less dense, with more light reaching the forest floor. They also contained no legume trees that we know of.

The asteroid created a void which was eventually, after about 10 million years, filled with more broadleaf flowering plants, including legumes.

Today, tropical coniferous forests are relatively rare habitats. Surprisingly, most of them are in Mexico, where the Chicxulub asteroid made impact.

node.text: With as many as 800 spoken languages, New York City - and Queens specifically - is the worldwide capital of linguistic diversity. Just 51% of New Yorkers speak English at home. 20% speak Spanish. For some endangered languages, like Yiddish and Nepal's Seke language, a large proportion of their speakers live in NYC. The city's Indigenous languages, Munsee and Unami, are critically endangered.
